# PHASE 4 — KARPENTER: CONTINUOUS COST-AWARE AUTOSCALING

## COMPLETE SRT — SERIES 4

```srt
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Welcome back to the course.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,000
In Series one, you built the foundation.
You learned what FinOps is. You learned the three phases.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:18,000
You learned unit economics. You built a tagging strategy.
You created your baseline document.

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:24,000
In Series two, you found the waste outside the cluster.
You migrated gp2 volumes to gp3.

5
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:30,000
You released unattached Elastic IPs.
You added VPC Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB.

6
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:36,000
You identified thousands of dollars in monthly waste.

7
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:42,000
In Series three, you deployed Kubecost.
You got visibility inside the cluster.

8
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:48,000
You saw cost per namespace. You saw cost per team.
You saw efficiency scores.

9
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:54,000
You applied rightsizing recommendations.
You reduced CPU requests by sixty percent.

10
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:00,000
You reduced memory requests by forty percent.

11
01:00:00,000 --> 01:06:00,000
But here's the thing about rightsizing.
It's a one-time fix.

12
01:06:00,000 --> 01:12:00,000
You reduce the CPU requests on a deployment.
The deployment restarts.

13
01:12:00,000 --> 01:18:00,000
The pods come up with the new resource requests.
The cluster now has more free capacity.

14
01:18:00,000 --> 01:24:00,000
But the nodes are still there.
The EC2 instances that were running before are still running.

15
01:24:00,000 --> 01:30:00,000
The EC2 instances that were added to handle the larger resource requests
are still there. You're still paying for them.

16
01:30:00,000 --> 01:36:00,000
You reduced the demand, but you didn't reduce the supply.

17
01:36:00,000 --> 01:42:00,000
You need something that continuously optimizes your compute.

18
01:42:00,000 --> 01:48:00,000
Something that watches your cluster's resource usage
in real time and automatically adjusts the underlying EC2 instances.

19
01:48:00,000 --> 01:54:00,000
Something that launches new instances when you need more capacity,
in seconds, not minutes.

20
01:54:00,000 --> 02:00:00,000
Something that removes instances when you don't need them,
without waiting for a long utilization threshold.

21
02:00:00,000 --> 02:06:00,000
Something that chooses the cheapest available instance type
from a list you provide, not just a single predefined type.

22
02:06:00,000 --> 02:12:00,000
Something that supports Spot instances natively,
so you can run fault-tolerant workloads at seventy percent off.

23
02:12:00,000 --> 02:18:00,000
That something is Karpenter.

24
02:18:00,000 --> 02:24:00,000
Series four is where you deploy Karpenter.
Karpenter is Kubernetes-native autoscaling.

25
02:24:00,000 --> 02:30:00,000
It's an open-source project from AWS.
It was announced at re:Invent in 2021.

26
02:30:00,000 --> 02:36:00,000
It reached general availability in 2022.
It's now used by thousands of companies, from startups to enterprises.

27
02:36:00,000 --> 02:42:00,000
And it replaces the traditional Cluster Autoscaler.
Completely. You don't need both. You just need Karpenter.

28
02:42:00,000 --> 02:48:00,000
Let me explain why the Cluster Autoscaler is costing you money.

29
02:48:00,000 --> 02:54:00,000
Most EKS clusters ship with the Cluster Autoscaler.
It was the standard for years.

30
02:54:00,000 --> 03:00:00,000
But it has three fundamental problems that cost you money
every single day.

31
03:00:00,000 --> 03:06:00,000
Problem one. It is slow.
The Cluster Autoscaler adds nodes only after pods fail to schedule.

32
03:06:00,000 --> 03:12:00,000
A pod enters Pending state. The autoscaler notices.
It calculates what instance size fits.

33
03:12:00,000 --> 03:18:00,000
It calls EC2. It waits for the instance to boot.
That process takes four to eight minutes.

34
03:18:00,000 --> 03:24:00,000
During those minutes, your users wait or your jobs queue.

35
03:24:00,000 --> 03:30:00,000
Problem two. It is rigid.
You define one instance type per node group. t3.large. That is it.

36
03:30:00,000 --> 03:36:00,000
If t4g.large ARM instances are twenty percent cheaper right now,
you cannot use them.

37
03:36:00,000 --> 03:42:00,000
If Spot prices dropped for m6i.xlarge, you cannot benefit.
The Cluster Autoscaler has no concept of price optimization.

38
03:42:00,000 --> 03:48:00,000
It just launches whatever you configured months ago.

39
03:48:00,000 --> 03:54:00,000
Problem three. It is slow to remove nodes.
The Cluster Autoscaler waits for a node to be underutilised
for a configurable period, typically ten to twenty minutes.

40
03:54:00,000 --> 04:00:00,000
Before removing it. During that window, you are paying for idle compute.

41
04:00:00,000 --> 04:06:00,000
On a busy cluster with frequent scaling events,
this idle time compounds into hundreds of dollars per month.

42
04:06:00,000 --> 04:12:00,000
Karpenter solves all three.

43
04:12:00,000 --> 04:18:00,000
It was built at AWS specifically because the Cluster Autoscaler
could not meet the cost and performance requirements
of large-scale Kubernetes at AWS.

44
04:18:00,000 --> 04:24:00,000
Speed. Karpenter watches the Kubernetes scheduler directly.
The moment a pod cannot schedule, Karpenter already knows.
In milliseconds.

45
04:24:00,000 --> 04:30:00,000
It launches a node in seconds, not minutes.

46
04:30:00,000 --> 04:36:00,000
Price optimization. You give Karpenter a list of instance families.
It queries EC2 Spot and On-Demand prices in real time.

47
04:36:00,000 --> 04:42:00,000
It picks the cheapest instance type that fits your pods.
Right now, not when you configured the cluster.

48
04:42:00,000 --> 04:48:00,000
Aggressive consolidation. Karpenter does not wait
for underutilisation thresholds.

49
04:48:00,000 --> 04:54:00,000
It continuously evaluates whether pods can be packed more tightly.
When they can, it drains a node, moves the pods,
and terminates the instance.

50
04:54:00,000 --> 05:00:00,000
Your cluster stays right-sized continuously, not periodically.

51
05:00:00,000 --> 05:06:00,000
Spot-native. Karpenter manages the Spot versus On-Demand split
as a first-class feature.

52
05:06:00,000 --> 05:12:00,000
You define capacity types. Karpenter handles the interruption signals,
cordon slash drain sequences, and fallback to On-Demand automatically.

53
05:12:00,000 --> 05:18:00,000
Let me give you the numbers from our startup story.

54
05:18:00,000 --> 05:24:00,000
After Series two and Series three, the startup's bill
was thirty-four thousand eight hundred dollars per month.

55
05:24:00,000 --> 05:30:00,000
Their compute situation before Karpenter.
Fifteen t3.large On-Demand nodes at eight point three two cents per hour.

56
05:30:00,000 --> 05:36:00,000
Cluster Autoscaler managing scale-out.
Nodes sitting at thirty-five to forty-five percent utilisation
most of the time.

57
05:36:00,000 --> 05:42:00,000
Monthly compute cost: four thousand three hundred twenty dollars.

58
05:42:00,000 --> 05:48:00,000
After deploying Karpenter with consolidation and Spot.
Five to eight nodes. Mix of t4g.large Spot and m6i.large On-Demand.

59
05:48:00,000 --> 05:54:00,000
Continuous consolidation removing idle nodes within thirty seconds.
Average cluster utilisation: seventy-two percent.

60
05:54:00,000 --> 06:00:00,000
Monthly compute cost: one thousand eight hundred ninety dollars.

61
06:00:00,000 --> 06:06:00,000
Compute savings: two thousand four hundred thirty dollars per month.
Twenty-nine thousand one hundred sixty dollars per year.

62
06:06:00,000 --> 06:12:00,000
From one afternoon of work.

63
06:12:00,000 --> 06:18:00,000
Combined with Series two and three,
the bill went from forty-seven thousand dollars to twenty thousand dollars.

64
06:18:00,000 --> 06:24:00,000
That is the story you will replicate.

65
06:24:00,000 --> 06:30:00,000
Now let me show you how to deploy it.

66
06:30:00,000 --> 06:36:00,000
Before we deploy Karpenter, you need a few things.
Let me walk through each prerequisite.

67
06:36:00,000 --> 06:42:00,000
First, you need an EKS cluster.
You should already have one from Series three.

68
06:42:00,000 --> 06:48:00,000
If you don't, go back and create one.
The GitHub repository for this course has Terraform configurations
for financial-rag-agent and riskoracle. Use those.

69
06:48:00,000 --> 06:54:00,000
Make sure your cluster is at least version 1.24 or newer.
Karpenter works best on recent Kubernetes versions.

70
06:54:00,000 --> 07:00:00,000
Second, you need Kubecost running.
You should already have this from Series three.

71
07:00:00,000 --> 07:06:00,000
Kubecost gives you the visibility you need to know
if Karpenter is working.

72
07:06:00,000 --> 07:12:00,000
You can see the node count drop in real time.
You can see the cost per namespace drop.

73
07:12:00,000 --> 07:18:00,000
You can see the efficiency scores improve.
Without Kubecost, you're flying blind.

74
07:18:00,000 --> 07:24:00,000
With Kubecost, you can see exactly how much money
Karpenter is saving you.

75
07:24:00,000 --> 07:30:00,000
Third, you need the AWS CLI configured with permissions
to launch EC2 instances.

76
07:30:00,000 --> 07:36:00,000
Karpenter needs to call EC2 APIs.
It needs to launch instances. It needs to terminate instances.

77
07:36:00,000 --> 07:42:00,000
It needs to tag instances. It needs to describe instances.
It needs to create launch templates.

78
07:42:00,000 --> 07:48:00,000
You should already have this from Series one and two.
If you can run aws ec2 describe-instances, you're probably fine.

79
07:48:00,000 --> 07:54:00,000
Fourth, you need IAM roles for Karpenter.
Karpenter runs inside your cluster as a set of pods.

80
07:54:00,000 --> 08:00:00,000
Those pods need permissions to call AWS APIs.
You can't just give them your AWS access keys. That's insecure.

81
08:00:00,000 --> 08:06:00,000
Instead, you create an IAM role.
You attach policies to that role.

82
08:06:00,000 --> 08:12:00,000
Then you associate that role with the Kubernetes service account
that Karpenter uses.

83
08:12:00,000 --> 08:18:00,000
This is called IAM roles for service accounts.
It's the standard way to give Kubernetes pods AWS permissions.

84
08:18:00,000 --> 08:24:00,000
First, you must remove the Cluster Autoscaler.
You cannot run Karpenter and the Cluster Autoscaler simultaneously.

85
08:24:00,000 --> 08:30:00,000
They will fight over nodes.

86
08:30:00,000 --> 08:36:00,000
Check if Cluster Autoscaler is running.
kubectl get deployment cluster-autoscaler dash n kube-system

87
08:36:00,000 --> 08:42:00,000
If it exists, remove it.
kubectl delete deployment cluster-autoscaler dash n kube-system

88
08:42:00,000 --> 08:48:00,000
Delete the cluster role binding, the cluster role,
and the service account.

89
08:48:00,000 --> 08:54:00,000
Verify removal.
kubectl get deployment cluster-autoscaler dash n kube-system

90
08:54:00,000 --> 09:00:00,000
Do not skip this step.
Running both autoscalers simultaneously causes a race condition.

91
09:00:00,000 --> 09:06:00,000
They continuously fight to add and remove the same nodes.
I have seen this cost a client eight thousand dollars
in a single weekend from a node thrashing loop.

92
09:06:00,000 --> 09:12:00,000
Now let's create the IAM role for Karpenter.

93
09:12:00,000 --> 09:18:00,000
First, get your cluster's OIDC provider ID.
OIDC stands for OpenID Connect.

94
09:18:00,000 --> 09:24:00,000
It's how Kubernetes authenticates with AWS.
Each EKS cluster has a unique OIDC provider.

95
09:24:00,000 --> 09:30:00,000
aws eks describe-cluster with name your cluster name
query cluster identity oidc issuer

96
09:30:00,000 --> 09:36:00,000
Extract the ID from the end of the URL.
OIDC_ID equals that ID.

97
09:36:00,000 --> 09:42:00,000
Now create the IAM policy document.
This defines what permissions Karpenter needs.

98
09:42:00,000 --> 09:48:00,000
The policy allows ec2:RunInstances, ec2:CreateFleet,
ec2:TerminateInstances.

99
09:48:00,000 --> 09:54:00,000
It allows ec2:DescribeInstances, ec2:DescribeInstanceTypes,
ec2:DescribeLaunchTemplates.

100
09:54:00,000 --> 10:00:00,000
It allows ec2:DescribeSubnets, ec2:DescribeSecurityGroups.
And iam:PassRole to pass the node IAM role to EC2 instances.

101
10:00:00,000 --> 10:06:00,000
Save this as karpenter-controller-policy.json.

102
10:06:00,000 --> 10:12:00,000
Now create the policy in AWS.
aws iam create-policy with policy name
KarpenterControllerPolicy dash your cluster name

103
10:12:00,000 --> 10:18:00,000
Policy document from the json file.
Get the policy ARN from the output. Write it down.

104
10:18:00,000 --> 10:24:00,000
Now create the trust policy.
The trust policy defines who can assume this role.

105
10:24:00,000 --> 10:30:00,000
We want the Kubernetes service account in the karpenter namespace
to assume it.

106
10:30:00,000 --> 10:36:00,000
The trust policy uses the OIDC provider ID we extracted.
It allows the service account system colon serviceaccount colon karpenter colon karpenter to assume the role.

107
10:36:00,000 --> 10:42:00,000
Save this as karpenter-trust-policy.json.

108
10:42:00,000 --> 10:48:00,000
Now create the IAM role.
aws iam create-role with role name
KarpenterControllerRole dash your cluster name

109
10:48:00,000 --> 10:54:00,000
Assume role policy document from the trust policy json.

110
10:54:00,000 --> 11:00:00,000
Now attach the policy to the role.
aws iam attach-role-policy with role name and policy ARN.

111
11:00:00,000 --> 11:06:00,000
Now create the node IAM role.
This role is assumed by the EC2 instances themselves.

112
11:06:00,000 --> 11:12:00,000
They need permissions to join the cluster,
pull images from ECR, and send logs to CloudWatch.

113
11:12:00,000 --> 11:18:00,000
Create the role with trust policy allowing ec2.amazonaws.com.

114
11:18:00,000 --> 11:24:00,000
Attach the required managed policies.
AmazonEKSWorkerNodePolicy, AmazonEKS_CNI_Policy,
AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryReadOnly, AmazonSSMManagedInstanceCore.

115
11:24:00,000 --> 11:30:00,000
Create an instance profile.
aws iam create-instance-profile with name
KarpenterNodeInstanceProfile dash your cluster name.

116
11:30:00,000 --> 11:36:00,000
Add the role to the instance profile.

117
11:36:00,000 --> 11:42:00,000
Now you have both IAM roles.
One for the Karpenter controller. One for the EC2 nodes.

118
11:42:00,000 --> 11:48:00,000
Karpenter needs an SQS queue to receive Spot interruption notifications
from AWS.

119
11:48:00,000 --> 11:54:00,000
Without this, it cannot proactively drain Spot nodes
before they are reclaimed.

120
11:54:00,000 --> 12:00:00,000
Pods get killed instead of gracefully migrated.

121
12:00:00,000 --> 12:06:00,000
Create the interruption queue.
aws sqs create-queue with queue name your cluster name.

122
12:06:00,000 --> 12:12:00,000
Message retention period three hundred seconds.
Five minutes is plenty. Spot warnings give you two minutes.

123
12:12:00,000 --> 12:18:00,000
Get the queue ARN. Then set the queue policy to allow EventBridge.

124
12:18:00,000 --> 12:24:00,000
Now create EventBridge rules for Spot interruption,
scheduled change, and state change.

125
12:24:00,000 --> 12:30:00,000
For each rule, set the event pattern.
For Spot interruption, source aws dot ec2,
detail-type EC2 Spot Instance Interruption Warning.

126
12:30:00,000 --> 12:36:00,000
For scheduled change, source aws dot health,
detail-type AWS Health Event.

127
12:36:00,000 --> 12:42:00,000
For state change, source aws dot ec2,
detail-type EC2 Instance State-change Notification.

128
12:42:00,000 --> 12:48:00,000
Add a target to each rule pointing to your SQS queue.

129
12:48:00,000 --> 12:54:00,000
Now Karpenter can listen for interruption signals.
When a Spot node is about to be reclaimed, Karpenter knows
with two minutes of warning.

130
12:54:00,000 --> 13:00:00,000
Now you need to tag your subnets and security groups.
Karpenter discovers subnets and security groups by tag.

131
13:00:00,000 --> 13:06:00,000
Without this, it cannot launch nodes.

132
13:06:00,000 --> 13:12:00,000
Get your VPC ID.
aws ec2 describe-vpcs filter non-default VPCs.

133
13:12:00,000 --> 13:18:00,000
Get all private subnet IDs.
For each subnet, add the tag karpenter.sh/discovery equals your cluster name.

134
13:18:00,000 --> 13:24:00,000
Get the node security group.
aws ec2 describe-security-groups with tag aws:eks:cluster-name.

135
13:24:00,000 --> 13:30:00,000
Add the same tag to the security group.

136
13:30:00,000 --> 13:36:00,000
Now Karpenter can find your subnets and security groups.

137
13:36:00,000 --> 13:42:00,000
Now install Karpenter using Helm.

138
13:42:00,000 --> 13:48:00,000
Set Karpenter version. Use v0.37.0. It is stable.

139
13:48:00,000 --> 13:54:00,000
Add the Karpenter Helm repository.
helm repo add karpenter https://charts.karpenter.sh

140
13:54:00,000 --> 14:00:00,000
helm repo update

141
14:00:00,000 --> 14:06:00,000
Install Karpenter from the OCI registry.
helm install karpenter oci://public.ecr.aws/karpenter/karpenter

142
14:06:00,000 --> 14:12:00,000
Version dash dash version, namespace karpenter, create namespace.

143
14:12:00,000 --> 14:18:00,000
Set settings.clusterName to your cluster name.
Set settings.interruptionQueue to your cluster name.

144
14:18:00,000 --> 14:24:00,000
Set serviceAccount annotations with the IAM role ARN.

145
14:24:00,000 --> 14:30:00,000
Set controller resources requests and limits.
One CPU, one gigabyte of memory.

146
14:30:00,000 --> 14:36:00,000
Wait for the installation.

147
14:36:00,000 --> 14:42:00,000
Verify the installation.
kubectl get pods dash n karpenter

148
14:42:00,000 --> 14:48:00,000
kubectl logs dash n karpenter dash l app.kubernetes.io/name=karpenter

149
14:48:00,000 --> 14:54:00,000
Expected log output shows Starting controller,
Connected to cluster, Starting informers.

150
14:54:00,000 --> 15:00:00,000
If you see IAM errors, your IRSA annotation or trust policy is wrong.
The most common mistake is a mismatch between the OIDC ID
in the role trust policy and the actual cluster OIDC ID.

151
15:00:00,000 --> 15:06:00,000
Now create the EC2NodeClass.
The EC2NodeClass tells Karpenter how to configure the EC2 instances
it launches.

152
15:06:00,000 --> 15:12:00,000
AMI, subnets, security groups, instance profile, user data.

153
15:12:00,000 --> 15:18:00,000
Use Amazon Linux 2023.
Better security posture than Amazon Linux 2.

154
15:18:00,000 --> 15:24:00,000
Set the role to the node IAM role we created.
KarpenterNodeRole dash your cluster name.

155
15:24:00,000 --> 15:30:00,000
Discover subnets by tag.
karpenter.sh/discovery equals your cluster name.

156
15:30:00,000 --> 15:36:00,000
Discover security groups by the same tag.

157
15:36:00,000 --> 15:42:00,000
Add tags to all nodes.
Name, Environment, ManagedBy, Team, CostCenter, Owner.

158
15:42:00,000 --> 15:48:00,000
These tags are critical for Cost Explorer attribution.
They also enforce the six tags from Series one.

159
15:48:00,000 --> 15:54:00,000
Block device. Use gp3, never gp2.
One hundred gigabytes. Three thousand IOPS. One hundred twenty-five throughput.

160
15:54:00,000 --> 16:00:00,000
Encrypted true. Delete on termination true.

161
16:00:00,000 --> 16:06:00,000
Always use encrypted true on node volumes.
In financial services environments, unencrypted EBS volumes
on worker nodes can be a SOC2 finding.

162
16:06:00,000 --> 16:12:00,000
Cost is negligible. There is no performance impact for gp3 with encryption.

163
16:12:00,000 --> 16:18:00,000
Apply the EC2NodeClass.
kubectl apply dash f dash dash filename

164
16:18:00,000 --> 16:24:00,000
Now create the NodePools.
NodePools define what nodes Karpenter is allowed to provision.

165
16:24:00,000 --> 16:30:00,000
Create separate NodePools for different workload types.
This is where cost optimization really happens.

166
16:30:00,000 --> 16:36:00,000
First, the application NodePool.
For your API and agent services.

167
16:36:00,000 --> 16:42:00,000
Requirements. Architecture amd64 and arm64.
Include ARM for cost savings.

168
16:42:00,000 --> 16:48:00,000
Instance families. Broad selection gives Karpenter more pricing options.
Graviton instances like m7g and c7g are about twenty percent cheaper
than x86 equivalents.

169
16:48:00,000 --> 16:54:00,000
Instance sizes. Large, xlarge, 2xlarge, 4xlarge.
Exclude nano, micro, small. Not suitable for production pods.

170
16:54:00,000 --> 17:00:00,000
Capacity types. Both on-demand and spot.

171
17:00:00,000 --> 17:06:00,000
Add a taint so only application pods schedule here.
key dedicated, value application, effect NoSchedule.

172
17:06:00,000 --> 17:12:00,000
Hard limits. CPU two hundred cores. Memory eight hundred gigabytes.
Prevent runaway scaling from a misconfigured HPA.

173
17:12:00,000 --> 17:18:00,000
Disruption. Consolidation policy WhenUnderutilized.
Consolidate after thirty seconds. Aggressive but appropriate for production.

174
17:18:00,000 --> 17:24:00,000
Expire after seven hundred twenty hours. Thirty days.
Nodes are replaced monthly with the latest Amazon Linux AMI.

175
17:24:00,000 --> 17:30:00,000
Weight one hundred. Higher weight means this NodePool is preferred.

176
17:30:00,000 --> 17:36:00,000
Now the ingestion NodePool.
For batch workloads like SEC EDGAR ingestion.

177
17:36:00,000 --> 17:42:00,000
Requirements. Compute-optimised instance families.
c5, c6i, c6a, c6g, c7i, c7g.

178
17:42:00,000 --> 17:48:00,000
Spot only. Batch jobs tolerate interruption with checkpointing.
We will cover checkpointing in Series five.

179
17:48:00,000 --> 17:54:00,000
Taint for ingestion workloads.
Consolidation policy WhenEmpty. Only consolidate when completely empty.

180
17:54:00,000 --> 18:00:00,000
In-flight ingestion jobs should not be interrupted mid-batch.
Consolidate after five minutes.

181
18:00:00,000 --> 18:06:00,000
Now the GPU NodePool for ML workloads.
For riskoracle's risk calculation engine.

182
18:06:00,000 --> 18:12:00,000
Requirements. GPU instance families.
g4dn, g5, p3, p4d.

183
18:12:00,000 --> 18:18:00,000
Spot preferred. Training jobs checkpoint every ten minutes.
They can tolerate interruption.

184
18:18:00,000 --> 18:24:00,000
Taint for GPU nodes. nvidia.com/gpu with effect NoSchedule.

185
18:24:00,000 --> 18:30:00,000
Consolidation policy WhenEmpty. Consolidate after two minutes.
Expire after twenty-four hours.

186
18:30:00,000 --> 18:36:00,000
Lower weight. Ten. Prefer cheaper instance types in other pools.

187
18:36:00,000 --> 18:42:00,000
Apply all three NodePools.

188
18:42:00,000 --> 18:48:00,000
Verify. kubectl get nodepool. kubectl get ec2nodeclass.

189
18:48:00,000 --> 18:54:00,000
Now add tolerations to your workloads.
NodePool taints mean pods need matching tolerations to schedule there.

190
18:54:00,000 --> 19:00:00,000
For the financial-rag-agent API, add the application toleration.
key dedicated, value application, effect NoSchedule.

191
